This screen shows the p5.js web editor interface with a code editor on the left and a preview canvas on the right.

**Code:**
The code is written in JavaScript using the p5.js library:
```javascript
let ufoArr = [];

class UFO {
  constructor(x, y, s) {
    this.x = x;
    this.y = y;
    this.s = s;
  }

  display() {
    push();
    noStroke();
    translate(this.s / 10);
    scale(this.s / 10);
    // draw top half
    fill(120, 120, 150);
    arc(0, 0, 30, 180, 0);
    arc(0, 50, 50, 180, 0);
    // draw bottom half
    fill(30, 30, 80);
    arc(0, 50, 100, 30, 0, 180);
    arc(0, 50, 50, 0, 180);
    // draw lights on the side
    fill(220, 150, 0);
    for (let x = -50; x <= 50; x += 10) {
      circle(x, 0, 5);
    }
  }
  pop();
}
```

**Visual output:**
The preview canvas displays a dark blue background filled with several stylized, layered clouds in shades of light and medium blue.

**UI state:**
The application is the p5.js web editor, with `sketch.js` as the active file. The console at the bottom shows an array containing multiple "UFO" objects: `(80) [UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, UFO, ...]`.

